le = The evolution of language: The cerebro-cerebellar blending of visual-spatial working memory with vocalizations | url = | journal = The Journal of Mind and Behavior | volume = 32 | issue = | pages = 317\u2013334 }}\n* Vandervert, L. (in press). How the blending of cerebellar internal models can explain the evolution of thought and language. Cerebellum.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Vandervert | first1 = L. | last2 = Schimpf | first2 = P. | last3 = Liu | first3 = H. | year = 2007 | title = How working memory and the cerebellum collaborate to produce creativity and innovation [Special Issue] | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/cfbb5a1010ccd7ad0a38c5c0abe9b09b6336d918| journal = Creativity Research Journal | volume = 19 | issue = 1| pages = 1\u201319 | doi=10.1080/10400410709336873}}\n* Vandervert, L., & Vandervert-Weathers, K. (in press). New brain-imaging studies indicate how prototyping is related to entrepreneurial giftedness and innovation education in children. In L. Shavinina (Ed.), The International Handbook of Innovation Education. London: Routlage.\n* {{cite book |author=DeGraff, J. |author2=Lawrence, K. |year=2002 |title=Creativity at Work |publisher=Jossey-Bass |isbn=978-0-7879-5725-4 |url=https://archive.org/details/creativityatwork00jeff_0 }}\n* Gielen, P. (2013). Creativity and other Fundamentalisms. Mondriaan: Amsterdam.\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=Creativity and Taoism, A Study of Chinese Philosophy, Art, and Poetry|last=Chung-yuan |first=Chang |date=1970 | publisher=Harper Torchbooks |location=New York|isbn=978-0-06-131968-6}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Dark Side of Creativity |editor1-last=Cropley |editor1-first=David H. |editor2-last=Cropley |editor2-first=Arthur J. |editor3-last=Kaufman |editor3-first=James C. |editor4-last=Runco |editor4-first=Mark A.| display-editors = 3 |year=2010 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |isbn=978-0-521-13960-1 |lay-url=http://www.cambridge.org/gb/knowledge/isbn/item2704083/?site_locale=en_GB |laydate=24 November 2010 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |title=Sudden Genius?: The Gradual Path to Creative Breakthroughs |last=Robinson |first=Andrew |year=2010 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-956995-3 |lay-url=http://ukcatalogue.oup.com/product/9780199569953.do |laydate=24 November 2010 |ref=harv |url=https://archive.org/details/suddengeniusgrad00robi_0 }}\n*[http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=creativity-roots-human-genius-deeper-than-expected ''The Roots of Human Genius Are Deeper Than Expected''] (March 10, 2013) [[Scientific American]]\n* {{cite book |title=Origins of Genius: Darwinian Perspectives on Creativity |author=Dean Keith Simonton |year=1999 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0195128796 |url=https://archive.org/details/originsofgeniusd00simo }}\n* [[Isaac Asimov]] (2014-10-20) [http://www.technologyreview.com/view/531911/isaac-asimov-mulls-how-do-people-get-new-ideas/ on Cultivating Creativity]\n* [[John Cleese]] (2014-08-08) [http://www.fastcocreate.com/1680999/4-lessons-in-creativity-from-john-cleese on Fostering Creativity]\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n;Videos\n* Raphael DiLuzio (2012-06-28) on [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MRD-4Tz60KE 7 Steps of Creative Thinking]\n\n{{Human intelligence topics}}\n{{aesthetics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Aptitude]]\n[[Category:Creativity| ]]\n[[Category:Cognition]]\n[[Category:Design]]\n[[Category:Educational psychology]]\n[[Category:Innovation economics]]\n[[Category:Innovation]]\n[[Category:Problem solving skills]]\n[[Category:Product management]]\n[[Category:Science and technology studies]]\n", "name_user": "D1119", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNeuroscience:fixed divergent thinking link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creativity"}
